title: Grateful Dead Live at Fillmore East on 1971-04-25
description: Set 1 Truckin', Loser, Hard To Handle, Me And Bobby McGee, Cold Rain & Snow, The Rub, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Casey Jones Set 2 Morning Dew, Beat It On Down The Line, Next Time You See Me, Bertha, Sugar Magnolia, Second That Emotion, Good Lovin'-> Drums-> Good Lovin', Sing Me Back Home, Not Fade Away-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> Not Fade Away Other artist(s): NRPS. This date is featured on Ladies and Gentlemen... The Grateful Dead.

reviews.review_text: no reviews? this is a great copy. touched up close to perfection. if you want a fantastic sounding copy of an April '71 Dead show, then this is the one you want!!
Great Great Great H2H Perhaps the ultimate HARD TO HANDLE

hey man! thanks for this really nice tape. we're sitting jamming the hell out of it. Peace. 
Gene and Bradley
Definitely not a bad show and a good recording, but hardly a stellar performance.

question for Phil (Matera) Excellent sound! Fabulous H2H!

Phil: you had the good sense not to isolate the drums in Good Lovin' in their own track. Why then, did you make the second part of the song (after the drums) a separate track?

So if I want to recreate the concert experience, I've got to become proficient with audio editing software to put all these pieces back into one seamless whole. But these shows began as (mostly) seamless reel-to-reel recordings.

Does this seem bass-ackwards to anyone?

Spring is in the air!!! That this show features what are likely the best-ever performances of Hard to Handle AND Good Lovin alone garners five stars. The improv in both of these songs is absolutely second-to-none, some of the band's greatest playing I've EVER heard in all my years of listening. A helluva way to kick off this legendary Fillmore East run!
GREAT SHOW :) One of my FAVORITE MORNING DEWs, and Sugar MAGS EVER>> WOW>> great show... PARADISE WAITS.
Very Nice, Spin It Highlights: Morning Dew, Second That Emotion, Sing Me Back Home

A man upon your scene.. 3rd stop in NyC area for 1971 and it was only late April.
one of the advantages of the Fillmore is it is relatively Hassle Free--Don't underestimate the Vibe!
The jam in Hard to Handle has been intense April 71
Jerry scorching it and Weir playing rhythm like he is on a Ukulele. 
Phil brings constant riff , Pig rapping, Billy letting loose on the skins.
Dig the tuning for FOTD and the banter
"A song we used to do acoustically"-Jer
Seems like Garcia has to work a little for those lyrics 
but jam is tight.
PIG plays some keys for China>Rider as Jerry and Phil 
lead the way into a straight a'head' jam.
Always felt you could get to GDTRFB from the C>R transition

This is a full night of music which gives the band numerous opportunities to stretch out.

anything that is wet and wiggles..
